{"cursor":"8563","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'Syrian people' ( / ALA-LC: al-shaâab al-SÅ«rÄ«) are the inhabitants and\ncitizens of the Syrian Arab Republic. While modern-day Syrians are commonly\ndescribed as Arabs by virtue of their modern-day language and bonds to Arab\nculture and history, they are, in fact, largely a blend of the various Aramaic,\nArab, and Arabic-speaking groups indigenous to the region. Most Syrians reside\nprimarily in Syria; however 17 million Syrians,\nmostly Christians live outside of Syria and they stay connected to their\ncultural roots by listening to Syrian music, watching Syrian Television, and\npreparing Syrian cuisine.\n\nDamascus, the capital of Syria, is one of the longest continuously inhabited\ncities [http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/198202/restoration.of.damasc-\nus.htm] [http://bostonglobe.longjaunt.com/photos/2008/05/28/damascus-\n/] in the world (for 8,000 years straight, Syrians inhabited Damascus),\nand a large percentage of Damascenes are the descendents of the early\ninhabitants of Damascus.\n","linknr":668,"url":"Syrian","recorded":1362373619,"links":36,"instances":["drink"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Syrian people","Ancient peoples","Fertile Crescent","Syrian society","Syrian diaspora","Semitic peoples","Indigenous peoples of Western Asia"],"headings":["Language","Religion","Beliefs","Cuisine","Famous people with Syrian ancestry","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Hashim_Al_Atassi.jpg/50px-Hashim_Al_Atassi.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Faris_al-Khoury.jpg/44px-Faris_al-Khoury.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Jamil_al-Ulshi.jpg/53px-Jamil_al-Ulshi.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Yusuf_Al_Azma.jpg/60px-Yusuf_Al_Azma.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Sultan_Pasha_al-Atrash.jpg/54px-Sultan_Pasha_al-Atrash.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/w